{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522849"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13851"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13851"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.35,0.01,0.04,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6468"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of increasing pain, swelling, and redness of her right breast. She reports feeling feverish but has not measured her temperature. Earlier in the year she underwent a right wide local excision and sentinel lymph node biopsy for breast cancer. She completed her adjuvant radiotherapy four weeks ago. She has a medical history of hypertension and takes amlodipine. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 98/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Her general inspection can be seen below (Image). She has an enlarged lymph node in the right axilla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Inflammatory breast cancer","Angiosarcoma","Paget\u0027s disease","Mastitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E of the right breast. The patient presents with classic signs of cellulitis, including erythema, warmth, pain, and swelling of the affected area. The presence of fever and the indistinct demarcation line at the edge of the redness are also typical features of cellulitis. The recent history of breast surgery and radiotherapy are significant risk factors for developing this condition. Radiotherapy can cause skin damage and impair local immune responses, making the area more susceptible to infection. The lymph node enlargement is likely reactionary to the cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory breast cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms, including breast swelling, redness, and warmth. However, it typically develops over weeks to months rather than days, and the patient\u0027s recent surgery and radiotherapy make cellulitis a more likely diagnosis in this acute setting. However if the swelling/erythema continued a dermal biopsy would be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare, aggressive malignancy of the blood or lymphatic vessels that can occur as a late complication of radiation therapy for breast cancer. However, it typically develops years after radiation treatment, not within weeks. Moreover, it usually presents as a bruise-like area or a raised purplish nodule, rather than the diffuse erythema and swelling seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E of the breast is a rare form of breast cancer that affects the nipple and areola. It typically presents with a scaly, red, itchy rash on the nipple that can extend to the areola. The presentation in this case, with widespread breast involvement and systemic symptoms, is not consistent with Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMastitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of breast tissue that can occur due to infection, often associated with breastfeeding. While it can present similarly to cellulitis, it is less common in non-lactating women, especially those who have recently undergone breast surgery and radiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECellulitis following breast surgery and radiotherapy is a known complication. Radiotherapy can cause skin damage, impair local immune responses, and alter the local vasculature, all of which can predispose the area to infection. Prompt recognition and treatment with appropriate antibiotics are crucial to prevent more serious complications such as abscess formation or sepsis. In cases of breast cellulitis or mastitis, follow-up imaging after the inflammation has settled should be performed to rule out underlying malignancy, although this is less likely in this case given the patient\u0027s recent treatment for known breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cellulitis is a common complication following breast surgery and radiotherapy.","Post-radiotherapy breast cellulitis typically presents with erythema, warmth, pain, and swelling of the affected breast.","Prompt recognition and treatment of post-radiotherapy breast cellulitis is crucial to prevent more serious complications.","In patients with cellulitis or mastitis who have not had recent imaging, follow up imaging once resolution of the inflammation has occurred is critical to ensure no underlying malignancy."],"references":["Skandhan A, Jones J, Kang O, et al. Breast cellulitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 03 Aug 2024). Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-cellulitis","Breastcancer.Org. Skin-associated infection (cellulitis). 2022. Available at: https://www.breastcancer.org/benign-breast-conditions/cellulitis","Cohen-Hallaleh RB, Smith HG, Smith RC, Stamp GF, Al-Muderis O, Thway K, Miah A, Khabra K, Judson I, Jones R, Benson C, Hayes AJ. Radiation induced angiosarcoma of the breast: outcomes from a retrospective case series. Clin Sarcoma Res. 2017. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5547463/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20798"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20798"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MZt5Bm0xb0GTaIiWlDdZNL3l4eOqQc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MZt5Bm0xb0GTaIiWlDdZNL3l4eOqQc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T15:36:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T15:37:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6468"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/107"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cellulitis","synonyms":["Skin infection"],"description":null,"position":null,"